ropists]]\n[[Category:American political fundraisers]]\n[[Category:American real estate businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American restaurateurs]]\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:American technology company founders]]\n[[Category:American United Methodists]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Aviation inventors]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Texas]]\n[[Category:Burials at Glenwood Cemetery (Houston, Texas)]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Houston]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:Collier Trophy recipients]]\n[[Category:Congressional Gold Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:Deaths from kidney failure]]\n[[Category:Engineers from California]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Texas]]\n[[Category:Film producers from California]]\n[[Category:History of Clark County, Nevada]]\n[[Category:History of Houston]]\n[[Category:Hypochondriacs]]\n[[Category:People from Ventura County, California]]\n[[Category:People with obsessive\u2013compulsive disorder]]\n[[Category:Rice University alumni]]\n[[Category:Survivors of aviation accidents or incidents]]\n[[Category:Texas Republicans]]\n[[Category:Trans World Airlines people]]\n[[Category:California Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Aviation pioneers]]\n[[Category:American aviation record holders]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People who died in office]]\n", "name_user": "Foxtod", "label": "safe", "comment": "corrected misspelling of his middle name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howard_Hughes"}
{"title_page": "University of Zadar", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name=University of Zadar\n| native_name=Sveu\u010dili\u0161te u Zadru\n| latin_name=Universitas Studiorum Jadertina\n| established={{start date and age|14 June 1396}}<small><br/>(2002 in present form)</small>\n| type=[[Public university|Public]]\n| staff= 213<ref name=\"unizd1\">{{cite web|author=O nama |url=http://www.unizd.hr/Onama/tabid/55/Default.aspx |title=O nama |publisher=Unizd.hr |date=2012-06-14 |accessdate=2017-03-01}}</ref>\n| rector= [[Dijana Vican]]\n| faculty=413<ref name=\"unizd1\"/>\n| students=c. 6,000<ref name=\"unizd1\"/>\n| city=[[Zadar]]\n| country=[[Croatia]]\n| campus=\n| affiliations=[[European University Association|EUA]] <br> [[Balkan Universities Network|BUN]]\n| website=[http://www.unizd.hr/ www.unizd.hr/] |\n|image = University of Zadar Logo.png}}\n\nThe '''University of Zadar''' ({{lang-hr|Sveu\u010dili\u0161te u Zadru}}, {{lang-la|Universitas Studiorum Iadertina}}) is a [[university]] located in [[Zadar]], [[Croatia]]. The university in its current modern form was founded in 2002, but can trace its lineage to 1396, thus making it the oldest tertiary institution in [[Croatia]] and one of the oldest in [[Europe]].\n\n== History ==\nThe original University of Zadar was founded by the [[Dominican Order|Dominicans]] in 1396 as ''Universitas Iadertina'', a [[Seminary|theological seminary]], Iadera being the Latin version of [[Zadar]]. The university was a continuation of the [[University of Dyrrachium]], in [[Durr\u00ebs]] (Dyrrhachium), [[Albania]], then [[Kingdom of Albania (medieval)|Medieval Kingdom of Albania]], which had been created around 1380, and then transferred to [[Zadar]] in 1396,  amid the mounting Turkish threats in South-eastern Europe, thereby becoming the University of Zadar.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.unizd.hr/Aboutus/tabid/5239/language/en-US/Default.aspx |title=University of Zadar : About us |website=Unizd.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-03-08}}</ref>\n\nIt was the first institute of higher learning in the country. In 1807 it ceased to become an independent institution and its functions were taken over by other local universities. In 1956 the [[University of Zagreb]], the country's second oldest university, re-established it as its satellite Faculty of Arts campus. The faculty later became a part of the [[University of Split]]. More than six centuries after the original university's founding, in 2002, the [[Croatian Parliament]] passed an act to allow for its re-founding as a full-fledged independent university. The new University of Zadar opened its doors to students in January 2003.<ref>[http://www.iro.hr/userdocs/File/ACCESS/tfarnell_UNIZD_ACCESS-dresden-FEB-2010.pdf University of Zadar]</ref>\n\nSince its reestablishment, the university has continued to grow from strength to strength. The [[Bologna process]] was implemented for the 2005-06 academic year as with all Croatian universities. A follow-up study a year later showed that the move greatly benefited University and has increased its profile internationally.<ref>[http://www.unizg.hr/bopro/activities/Zadar_3.pdf Bologna Process at the University of Zadar - A year later]. November 2006.</ref> This allowed it to engage in collaborative research agreements and [[student exchange program]]mes with other reputable universities around the continent. It also has agreements with universities in [[South America]] and the [[United States]]. First Croatian president, [[Franjo Tu\u0111man]], graduated on University of Zadar on 28 December 1965, which was then part of [[University of Zagreb]].\n\n== Faculties ==\n\nToday, the University of Zadar is the largest integrated university in the Republic of Croatia, which includes 25 university departments:\n\n* Department of [[Archaeology]]\n* Department of [[Classical Philology]]\n** Division of [[Greek language|Greek Language]] and Literature\n** Division of Latin Language and Literature\n* Department of [[Croatia]]n and [[Slavic Studies]]\n** Division of [[Croatian language|Croatian Language]] and Literature\n** Division of [[Russian language|Russian Language]] and Literature\n* Department of Ecology, [[Agronomy]] and [[Aquaculture]]\n* Department of [[Economics]]\n* Department of [[English language|English]]\n* Department of [[Ethnology]] and [[Anthropology]]\n* Department of [[French Language]] and [[Iberian Romance languages|Ibero-Romance Studies]]\n** Division of [[French language|French Language]] and Literature\n** Division of [[Iberian Romance languages|Iberoromance]] Studies\n* Department of [[Geography]]\n* Department of [[German Studies]]\n* Department of Health Studies\n* Department of [[History]]\n* Department of [[History]] of [[Art]]\n* Department of [[Information Sciences]] \n* Department of [[Italian Studies]] \n* Department of [[Linguistics]]\n* Maritime department \n** Division of Nautical Studies\n** Division of [[Offshore construction|Maritime Engineering]]\n* Department of [[Pedagogy]]\n* Department of [[Philosophy]]\n* Department of [[Psychology]]\n* Department of Religious Sciences\n* Department of [[Sociology]]\n* Department of Teacher Education Studies in [[Gospi\u0107]]\n* Department of Teachers and [[Preschool]] Teachers Education\n** Division of [[Elementary school|Elementary School]] Teacher Education\n** Division of Preschool Teacher Education\n*  Department of [[Tourism]] and [[Communication Studies]]\n\nIn order to organise and promote scientific-research activities, the university has founded four scientific-research centres as its constituent units. These include: the Centre for Adriatic Onomastic Research, Centre Stjepan Mati\u010devi\u0107, Centre for Karst and Coastal Research and Centre for Interdisciplinary Marine and Maritime Research - CIMMAR.\n\nIn addition, there are two active centres for professional and teaching activities: the Centre for [[Gymnastics]] and Student Sport and the Centre for [[Foreign language|Foreign Languages]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of universities in Croatia]]\n* [[Zadar]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.unizd.hr University of Zadar Website] {{in lang|hr|en}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091028043456/http://ling.unizd.hr/ Department of Linguistics at the University of Zadar Website] {{in lang|pl|de|hr|en}}\n* [http://www.infozadar.net Info Zadar] {{in lang|hr}}\n\n{{Cro_Uni}}\n{{Balkan Universities Network}}\n{{coord|44.1131|N|15.2251|E|source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zadar, University of}}\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 14th century]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Croatia]]\n[[Category:University of Zadar| ]]\n[[Category:1396 establishments in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox University\n| name=University of Zadar\n| native_name=Sveu\u010dili\u0161te u Zadru\n| latin_name=Universitas Studiorum Jadertina\n| established={{start date and age|14 June 1396}}<small><br/>(2002 in present form)</small>\n| type=[[Public university|Public]]\n| staff= 213<ref name=\"unizd1\">{{cite web|author=O nama |url=http://www.unizd.hr/Onama/tabid/55/Default.aspx |title=O nama |publisher=Unizd.hr |date=2012-06-14 |accessdate=2017-03-01}}</ref>\n| rector= [[Dijana Vican]]\n| faculty=413<ref name=\"unizd1\"/>\n| students=c. 6,000<ref name=\"unizd1\"/>\n| city=[[Zadar]]\n| country=[[Croatia]]\n| campus=\n| affiliations=[[European University Association|EUA]] <br> [[Balkan Universities Network|BUN]]\n| website=[http://www.unizd.hr/ www.unizd.hr/] |\n|image = University of Zadar Logo.png}}\n\nThe '''University of Zadar''' ({{lang-hr|Sveu\u010dili\u0161te u Zadru}}, {{lang-la|Universitas Studiorum Iadertina}}) is a [[university]] located in [[Zadar]], [[Croatia]]. The university in its current modern form was founded in 2002, but can trace its lineage to 1396, thus making it the oldest tertiary institution in [[Croatia]] and one of the oldest in [[Europe]].\n\n== History ==\nThe original University of Zadar was founded by the [[Dominican Order|Dominicans]] in 1396 as ''Universitas Iadertina'', a [[Seminary|theological seminary]], Iadera being the Latin version of [[Zadar]]. The university was a continuation of the [[University of Dyrrachium]], in [[Durr\u00ebs]] (Dyrrhachium), [[Albania]], then [[Kingdom of Albania (medieval)|Medieval Kingdom of Albania]], which had been created around 1380, and then transferred to [[Zadar]] in 1396,  amid the mounting Turkish threats in South-eastern Europe, thereby becoming the University of Zadar.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.unizd.hr/Aboutus/tabid/5239/language/en-US/Default.aspx |title=University of Zadar : About us |website=Unizd.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-03-08}}</ref>\n\nIt was the first institute of higher learning in the country. In 1807 it ceased to become an independent institution and its functions were taken over by other local universities. In 1956 the [[University of Zagreb]], the country's second oldest university, re-established it as its satellite Faculty of Arts campus. The faculty later became a part of the [[University of Split]]. More than six centuries after the original university's founding, in 2002, the [[Croatian Parliament]] passed an act to allow for its re-founding as a full-fledged independent university. The new University of Zadar opened its doors to students in January 2003.<ref>[http://www.iro.hr/userdocs/File/ACCESS/tfarnell_UNIZD_ACCESS-dresden-FEB-2010.pdf University of Zadar]</ref>\n\nSince its reestablishment, the university has continued to grow from strength to strength. The [[Bologna process]] was implemented for the 2005-06 academic year as with all Croatian universities. A follow-up study a year later showed that the move greatly benefited University and has increased its profile internationally.<ref>[http://www.unizg.hr/bopro/activities/Zadar_3.pdf Bologna Process at the University of Zadar - A year later]. November 2006.</ref> This allowed it to engage in collaborative research agreements and [[Student exchange program|student exchange programmes]] with other reputable universities around the continent. It also has agreements with universities in [[South America]] and the [[United States]]. First Croatian president, [[Franjo Tu\u0111man]], graduated on University of Zadar on 28 December 1965, which was then part of [[University of Zagreb]].\n\n== Faculties ==\n\nToday, the University of Zadar is the largest integrated university in the Republic of Croatia, which includes 25 university departments:\n\n* Department of [[Archaeology]]\n* Department of [[Classical Philology]]\n** Division of [[Greek language|Greek Language]] and Literature\n** Division of Latin Language and Literature\n* Department of [[Croatia]]n and [[Slavic Studies]]\n** Division of [[Croatian language|Croatian Language]] and Literature\n** Division of [[Russian language|Russian Language]] and Literature\n* Department of Ecology, [[Agronomy]] and [[Aquaculture]]\n* Department of [[Economics]]\n* Department of [[English language|English]]\n* Department of [[Ethnology]] and [[Anthropology]]\n* Department of [[French Language]] and [[Iberian Romance languages|Ibero-Romance Studies]]\n** Division of [[French language|French Language]] and Literature\n** Division of [[Iberian Romance languages|Iberoromance]] Studies\n* Department of [[Geography]]\n* Department of [[German Studies]]\n* Department of Health Studies\n* Department of [[History]]\n* Department of [[History]] of [[Art]]\n* Department of [[Information Sciences]] \n* Department of [[Italian Studies]] \n* Department of [[Linguistics]]\n* Maritime department \n** Division of Nautical Studies\n** Division of [[Offshore construction|Maritime Engineering]]\n* Department of [[Pedagogy]]\n* Department of [[Philosophy]]\n* Department of [[Psychology]]\n* Department of Religious Sciences\n* Department of [[Sociology]]\n* Department of Teacher Education Studies in [[Gospi\u0107]]\n* Department of Teachers and [[Preschool]] Teachers Education\n** Division of [[Elementary school|Elementary School]] Teacher Education\n** Division of Preschool Teacher Education\n*  Department of [[Tourism]] and [[Communication Studies]]\n\nIn order to organise and promote scientific-research activities, the university has founded four scientific-research centres as its constituent units. These include: the Centre for Adriatic Onomastic Research, Centre Stjepan Mati\u010devi\u0107, Centre for Karst and Coastal Research and Centre for Interdisciplinary Marine and Maritime Research - CIMMAR.\n\nIn addition, there are two active centres for professional and teaching activities: the Centre for [[Gymnastics]] and Student Sport and the Centre for [[Foreign language|Foreign Languages]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of universities in Croatia]]\n* [[Zadar]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.unizd.hr University of Zadar Website] {{in lang|hr|en}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091028043456/http://ling.unizd.hr/ Department of Linguistics at the University of Zadar Website] {{in lang|pl|de|hr|en}}\n* [http://www.infozadar.net Info Zadar] {{in lang|hr}}\n\n{{Cro_Uni}}\n{{Balkan Universities Network}}\n{{coord|44.1131|N|15.2251|E|source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zadar, University of}}\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 14th century]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Croatia]]\n[[Category:University of Zadar| ]]\n[[Category:1396 establishments in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Zadar"}
{"title_page": "University of World Economy and Diplomacy", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name              = '''University of World Economy and Diplomacy (UWED)'''\n|native_name       =\n|image_name        =\n|image_size        = 200px\n|caption           =\n|latin_name        =\n|motto             =\n|mottoeng          =\n|established       = 1992\n|closed            =\n|type              = National\n|affiliation       =\n|endowment         =\n|officer_in_charge =\n|chairman          =\n|chancellor        =\n|president         = \n|vice-president    =\n|superintendent    =\n|provost           =\n|vice_chancellor   =\n|rector            = \n|principal         =\n|deans             =\n|director          =\n|head_label        =\n|head              =\n|staff             =\n|students          =\n|undergrad         =\n|postgrad          =\n|doctoral          =\n|other             =\n|city              = {{flagicon|Uzbekistan}} [[Tashkent]]\n|state             =\n|province          =\n|country           = [[Uzbekistan]]\n|coor              =\n|campus            =\n|former_names      =\n|free_label        =\n|free              =\n|sports            =\n|colors            =\n|colours           =\n|nickname          =\n|mascot            =\n|athletics         =\n|affiliations      =\n|website           = http://www.uwed.uz   \n|logo              =\n|footnotes         =\n}}\n\nThe '''University of World Economy and Diplomacy''' is located in [[Tashkent]], the capital of [[Uzbekistan]]. It was founded in September 23, 1992 by the decree of the [[President (government title)|President]] [[Islam Karimov|Karimov]] to train future leaders of the country.\n\nThe [[University]] of [[World]] [[Economy]] and [[Diplomacy]] is a [[public university|public]] institution which provides [[education]] that serves the interests of foreign policy of [[Uzbekistan]] and contributes to the development of society and the individual.\nThe University has a strong alumni network.\n\n==Academics==\nUWED has completed the transition to a comprehensive system of education, offering five-year degree program at the undergraduate as well as two-year master's degree program. The university maintains sufficient depth of scholarship to offer the doctorate in selected academic disciplines.\n\nThe training on the subjects of international relations, political science, global [[economy]], and [[law]] is conducted by three departments, 22 chair departments, and eight centers and is given by 16 full professors, more than 70 holders of Doctor or Candidate of Sciences degrees, 55 associate professors and 87 qualified faculty members. Faculties for bachelor's degrees are [[International Economic Relations]], international relations, and [[International law]].\n\n==Sources==\nFaculty training<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiut.uz/en/partners/uwed/ |title=Westminster International University in Tashkent (WIUT) |publisher=Wiut.uz |date= |accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref>\n\nSource<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.em-silkroute.eu/en/central-asian-universities-requirements-and-hospitality/13-contenuti/37-university-of-world-economy-and-diplomacy-uzbekistan.html |title=University of World Economy and Diplomacy, Uzbekistan |publisher=Em-silkroute.eu |date=2013-11-25 |accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Tashkent}}\n*[[Inha University in Tashkent]]\n*[[Tashkent State Technical University]]\n*[[Tashkent Institute of Irrigation and Melioration]]\n*[[Tashkent Financial Institute]]\n*[[Moscow State University in Tashkent named M.V Lomonosov]]\n*[[Tashkent Automobile and Road Construction Institute]]\n*[[Tashkent State University of Economics]]\n*[[Tashkent State Agrarian University]]\n*[[Tashkent State University of Law]]\n*[[Tashkent University of Information Technologies]]\n*[[Westminster International University in Tashkent]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{World topic|List of universities in}}\n{{Asia topic|List of universities in}}\n{{coord|41|19|26|N|69|19|11|E|region:KZ_source:kolossus-jawiki|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Uzbekistan]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1992]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox University\n|name              = '''University of World Economy and Diplomacy (UWED)'''\n|native_name       =\n|image_name        =\n|image_size        = 200px\n|caption           =\n|latin_name        =\n|motto             =\n|mottoeng          =\n|established       = 1992\n|closed            =\n|type              = National\n|affiliation       =\n|endowment         =\n|officer_in_charge =\n|chairman          =\n|chancellor        =\n|president         = \n|vice-president    =\n|superintendent    =\n|provost           =\n|vice_chancellor   =\n|rector            = \n|principal         =\n|deans             =\n|director          =\n|head_label        =\n|head              =\n|staff             =\n|students          =\n|undergrad         =\n|postgrad          =\n|doctoral          =\n|other             =\n|city              = {{flagicon|Uzbekistan}} [[Tashkent]]\n|state             =\n|province          =\n|country           = [[Uzbekistan]]\n|coor              =\n|campus            =\n|former_names      =\n|free_label        =\n|free              =\n|sports            =\n|colors            =\n|colours           =\n|nickname          =\n|mascot            =\n|athletics         =\n|affiliations      =\n|website           = http://www.uwed.uz   \n|logo              =\n|footnotes         =\n}}\n\nThe '''University of World Economy and Diplomacy''' is located in [[Tashkent]], the capital of [[Uzbekistan]]. It was founded in September 23, 1992 by the decree of the [[President (government title)|President]] [[Islam Karimov|Karimov]] to train future leaders of the country.\n\nThe [[University]] of [[World]] [[Economy]] and [[Diplomacy]] is a [[public university|public]] institution which provides [[education]] that serves the interests of foreign policy of [[Uzbekistan]] and contributes to the development of society and the individual.\nThe University has a strong alumni network.\n\n==Academics==\nUWED has completed the transition to a comprehensive system of education, offering five-year degree program at the undergraduate as well as two-year master's degree program. The university maintains sufficient depth of scholarship to offer the doctorate in selected academic disciplines.\n\nThe training on the subjects of international relations, political science, global [[economy]], and [[law]] is conducted by three departments, 22 chair departments, and eight centers and is given by 16 full professors, more than 70 holders of Doctor or Candidate of Sciences degrees, 55 associate professors and 87 qualified faculty members. Faculties for bachelor's degrees are [[International Economic Relations]], international relations, and [[International law]].\n\n==Sources==\nFaculty training<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiut.uz/en/partners/uwed/ |title=Westminster International University in Tashkent (WIUT) |publisher=Wiut.uz |date= |accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref>\n\nSource<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.em-silkroute.eu/en/central-asian-universities-requirements-and-hospitality/13-contenuti/37-university-of-world-economy-and-diplomacy-uzbekistan.html |title=University of World Economy and Diplomacy, Uzbekistan |publisher=Em-silkroute.eu |date=2013-11-25 |accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Tashkent}}\n*[[Inha University in Tashkent]]\n*[[Tashkent State Technical University]]\n*[[Tashkent Institute of Irrigation and Melioration]]\n*[[Tashkent Financial Institute]]\n*[[Moscow State University in Tashkent named M.V Lomonosov]]\n*[[Tashkent Automobile and Road Construction Institute]]\n*[[Tashkent State University of Economics]]\n*[[Tashkent State Agrarian University]]\n*[[Tashkent State University of Law]]\n*[[Tashkent University of Information Technologies]]\n