{"title_page": "University of Winnipeg", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=February 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2007}}\n{{Coord|49|53|24.44|N|97|9|12.12|W|display=title|type:edu}}\n{{Infobox university\n| image          = Uof Winnepeg CoA.svg\n| name           = University of Winnipeg\n| motto          = ''Lux et Veritas Floreant'' \n| mottoeng       = Let Light and Truth Flourish\n| established    = 1871 Manitoba College. Subsequent names, Wesley College (1881), United College (1938), and now, The University of Winnipeg (1967\u2013present)\n| type           = [[Public university|Public]]\n| president      = [[Annette Trimbee]]\n| city           = [[Winnipeg]]\n| province       = [[Manitoba]]\n| country        = Canada\n| students       = 9,419<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/about/fast-facts/index.html</ref>\n| undergrad      = 9,137<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/about/fast-facts/index.html</ref>\n| postgrad       = 282<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/about/fast-facts/index.html</ref>\n| academic_staff = 305<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/about/fast-facts/index.html</ref>\n| administrative_staff = 494<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/about/fast-facts/index.html</ref>\n| campus         = Urban\n| mascot         = Wesley Coyote\n| free_label     = Sports team\n| free           = [[Winnipeg Wesmen]]\n| affiliations   = [[Association of Universities and Colleges of Canada|AUCC]], [[International Association of Universities|IAU]], [[Association of Theological Schools in the United States and Canada|ATS]], [[U Sports]], [[Canada West Universities Athletic Association|CWUAA]], [[University of the Arctic|UArctic]], [[Campus Manitoba]], [[Canadian University Press|CUP]], [[Gallery 1C03]]\n| endowment      = [[Canadian dollar|$]]64.7 million<ref>{{cite web|title=The University of Winnipeg Foundation: 2017-2018 Annual Endowment report|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/foundation/docs/annual-report-2018-final.pdf|publisher=''The University of Winnipeg Foundation |accessdate= 28 June 2019}}</ref>\n| website        = {{URL|https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/}}\n| logo           = Uof Winnepeg Logo.svg\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Winnipeg''' ('''UWinnipeg''', '''U of W''') is a [[public research university]] in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], Canada, that offers undergraduate faculties of art, business and economics, education, science and kinesiology and applied health as well as graduate programs. UWinnipeg's founding colleges were [[Manitoba College]] and [[Wesley College, Winnipeg|Wesley College]], which merged to form [[United College, Winnipeg|United College]] in 1938. The University of Winnipeg was established in 1967 when United College received its charter. The governance was modeled on the provincial [[University of Toronto]] Act of 1906 which established a bicameral system of university government consisting of a senate (faculty), responsible for academic policy, and a board of governors (citizens) exercising exclusive control over financial policy and having formal authority in all other matters. The president, appointed by the board, was a link between the bodies to perform institutional leadership.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/ |title=The Canadian Encyclopedia |encyclopedia=The Canadian Encyclopedia |date=1936-02-07 |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref>\n\nThe University's current president and vice-chancellor, [[Annette Trimbee]], announced her resignation in March 2020. UWinnipeg's interim president will be James Currie, vice-president academic and provost until a new president is appointed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/university-winnipeg-president-resigns-1.5483785|title=University of Winnipeg president to leave job in July|last=|first=|date=March 3, 2020|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n[[Maclean's|''Maclean's'' magazine]] and ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' newspaper consistently rank the university in the top fifteen of all Canadian universities whose primary focus is undergraduate education in the category of student satisfaction. In 2013 the U of W ranked 13th out of 19 primarily undergraduate institutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oncampus.macleans.ca/education/2012/11/01/2013-primarily-undergraduate/. |title = 2013 Primarily undergraduate ranking |author = Maclean's |accessdate=8 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:UniversityofWinnipegFront.jpg|left|thumb|The University of Winnipeg]]\nThe U of W's founding colleges were [[Manitoba College]], 1871, and [[Wesley College, Winnipeg|Wesley College]], 1888, which merged to form United College in 1938.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/about/fast-facts/index.html|title=UWinnipeg Fast Facts|publisher=University of Winnipeg|accessdate=2016-10-20}}</ref><ref>Friesen, Gerald. \"Principal J. H. Riddell: The Sane and Safe Leader of Wesley College.\" In Prairie Spirit: Perspectives on the Heritage of the United Church of Canada in the West, edited by Dennis L. Butcher, et al. Winnipeg: University of Manitoba Press, 1985.</ref> In 1967, United College received a charter and became the University of Winnipeg. George Creeford Browne (architect) & S. Frank Peters designed Wesley Hall (1894\u20135), which is now part of the University of Winnipeg.<ref>[http://dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org/architects/view/1223 George Creeford Browne (architect) & S. Frank Peters]</ref>\n\nThe University of Winnipeg was established on 1 July 1967<ref>{{cite book|title=Fitzhenry and Whiteside Book of Canadian Facts and Dates|last=Pound|first=Richard W.|publisher=Fitzhenry and Whiteside|year=2005}}</ref> when United College received its charter.<ref name=\"Bedford, A. G 1976\">Bedford, A. G. The University of Winnipeg: A History of the Founding Colleges. Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1976.</ref>\nUnited College was formed in 1938 from the union of Manitoba College, founded in 1871, and Wesley College, founded in 1888. Originally affiliated with the [[University of Manitoba]], United College received its charter in 1967 and became the University of Winnipeg.<ref name=\"Bedford, A. G 1976\" />\n\n==Campus==\n[[File: Rice Centre.jpg|thumb|right|Rice Centre with the Buhler Centre seen in the back]]\n[[File:UofWRear.JPG|thumb|right|University of Winnipeg seen from Ellice Avenue]] \n[[File:UWBuhlerCentre.JPG|thumb|right|University of Winnipeg Buhler Centre]] \n[[File:UWTheatreandFilm.JPG|thumb|right|University of Winnipeg Theatre & Film]]\n\nThe campus of The University of Winnipeg is made up of 23 buildings spreading over several full blocks of [[Downtown Winnipeg]], located directly on [[Portage Avenue]].<ref>https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/map/docs/campus-map.pdf</ref> Over the past decade, the campus has undergone over 10 new building construction or major renovation projects. Through its revitalization, the University has become an engine for downtown renewal and improvement.<ref>http://uwcrc.ca/projects</ref>\n\nWesley Hall is a stone-clad brick structure built in 1894\u201395 and is on the Registry of Historic Places of Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=8224&pid=0|title=Wesley Hall|publisher=Canada's Historic Places|accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref> It is located on 515 Portage Ave. near [[Portage Place]] Mall.\n\nThe Buhler Centre was constructed to house the Faculty of Business and Economics, as well as PACE (Professional, Applied and Continuing Education), a division of the University of Winnipeg. The doors to the Buhler Centre opened September 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/index/campus-development-buhler-centre|title=Campus Development Buhler Centre|publisher=University of Winnipeg|accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref> Designed by PSA+DPA+DIN collective a collaborative effort between Peter Sampson Architecture Studio inc, David Penner Architect, and DIN Projects. The Buhler Centre also houses the Plug In Institute of Contemporary Art and Stella's Cafe on the main floor.\n\nThe Institute for stained glass in Canada has documented the stained glass at the University of Winnipeg. Specifically at the convocation hall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stainedglasscanada.ca/site.php?site=184/|title=Institute for stained glass in Canada|accessdate=16 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the university announced that Raymond L. McFeetors, Chairman of [[Great West Life|The Great West Life Assurance Company]], had donated $2.67 Million for a dormitory to be built on newly acquired property west of the campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/index/release-080502.|title=Ray McFeetors, Great West Life|author=University of Winnipeg|accessdate=13 July 2008}}</ref> The money came from his personal resources and from Great West Life.\n\n==Campus development==\n\n[[File: Marsha Hanen Way.jpg|thumb|right|Marsha Hanen Way with the Health & RecPlex in the back.]]\n[[File:Balmoral Transit Terminal at the University of Winnipeg.jpg|thumb|right| Balmoral University Transit Terminal]]\n\nCampus development, by the University of Winnipeg, is headed by The University of Winnipeg Renewal Corporation (UWCRC), \"a not-for-profit charitable corporation, spearheads and manages campus development.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/campus-development/|title=Campus Development \u2013 The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-11}}</ref> The UWCRC is a not-for-profit subsidiary of the University of Winnipeg and works to achieve environmental, social, economic and cultural sustainability. Their mandate is to \"apply [the UWCRC's] values, skills, competencies, and experience to non-University specific economic development activities. [UWCRC] is mandated to develop wholly owned or joint-venture real estate developments and to provide development, project management and property management services to other post-secondary institutions, non-profit organizations and First Nations clients.\"<ref name=\"uwinnipeg.ca\">{{Cite web|url=http://uwcrc.ca/what-we-do|title=What We Do {{!}} The University of Winnipeg Community Renewal Corporation|website=uwcrc.ca|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-11}}</ref>\n\nThe university president sits as the chair of the corporation and participates in its business partnerships.\n\nThe structure of the UWCRC is unique in Canada as it allows the corporation to avoid being governed by the strictures of university governance.<ref name=\"uwinnipeg.ca\" /> The corporation serves as \"a primary engine for the redevelopment of Winnipeg\u2019s downtown\", a task traditionally undertaken by government and the private sector, and not educational institutions.<ref name=\"uwinnipeg.ca\" />\n\nRecent initiatives include the newly renovated Asper Centre for Theater and Film, Richardson College for the Environment and Science Complex, The Axworthy Health and RecPlex, McFeetors Hall (a new student residence) and the UWSA Daycare.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/campus-development/|title=Campus Development \u2013 The University of Winnipeg|last=|first=|date=|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-11}}</ref> A new mixed use 14-story apartment complex for students and the community began construction in 2015.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nThe financial statements of the corporation are not publicly available under public disclosure legislation. The corporate draws its operating funds entirely from the university budget.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/financial-services/financial-statements.html|title=Audited Financial Statements and Other Financial Information - Financial Services, The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca}}</ref>\n\n==Academic==\n===Students and faculty===\nStudents at the university are represented by the University of Winnipeg Students' Association.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theuwsa.ca|title=The University of Winnipeg's Student Association|accessdate=16 February 2010}}</ref> [[CKUW]] is the [[student radio]] station based at the University of Winnipeg. The Uniter is the campus newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uniter.ca/|title=The Uniter|accessdate=16 February 2010}}</ref> The Student Services staff are represented by AESES.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aeses.ca/|title=Home - Association of Employees Supporting Education Services|website=Association of Employees Supporting Education Services}}</ref>\n\n===Faculties===\n* Faculty of Arts\n* Faculty of Education\n* Gupta Faculty of Kinesiology and Applied Health \n* Faculty of Science\n* Faculty of Graduate Studies\n* [[University of Winnipeg's Faculty of Business and Economics]]\n\n===Colleges===\n* Global College\n* Menno Simons College\n* Richardson College for the Environment\n\n===Centres and institutes===\n* Centre for Academic Writing (CAW)\n* Centre for Distributed / Distance Learning (CDDL)\n* Centre for Forest Interdisciplinary Research (C-FIR)\n* Centre for Innovation in Teaching & Learning (CITL)\n* Centre for Learning and Secular Society (CLASS)\n* Centre for Research in Young People's Texts and Cultures (CRYTC)\n* Centre for Rupert's Land Studies\n* Centre for Sustainable Transportation\n* Centre for Terrestrial and Planetary Exploration (C-TAPE)\n* Institute of Urban Studies\n* Institute for Women's and Gender Studies\n* India Centre for Academic, Business, and Community Excellence\n\n=== Graduate programs ===\n* Masters of Arts in Cultural Studies\n* Master of Arts in Indigenous Governance\n* Master of Arts in Environmental, Resource, and Developmental Economics (ERDE)\n* Master of Arts in Criminal Justice (as of Fall 2018)\n* Master of Science in Applied Computer Science and Society\n* Master of Science in Bioscience, Technology and Public Policy\n* Master's in Development Practice: Indigenous Development\n* Master's in Management: Technology, Innovation and Operations.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/graduate-studies/graduate-programs/|title=Programs Overview {{!}} Graduate Studies , The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref>\nMaster in Sacred Theology and Master of Arts Spiritual Disciplines & Ministry Practices are under review. Applications are not currently being accepted by the University of Winnipeg.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n==== Joint programs with the University of Manitoba ====\n* Master of Arts in History\n* Master of Public Administration\n* Master of Arts in Religious Studies\n* Master of Arts in Peace and Conflict Studies<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n==== Postgraduate certificates ====\n* The Higher Education Teaching Certificate\n* The Postgraduate Professional Skills Certificate<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n==Indigenous UWinnipeg ==\nThe University of Winnipeg offers several programs and services to Aboriginal people. It is the first university to mandate that all students take an Indigenous course requirement as part of their degree. The course was added by the University of Winnipeg in support and compliance with the recommendations by the [[Truth and Reconciliation Commission of Canada]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/indigenous-course-requirement/index.html|title=Home {{!}} Indigenous Course Requirement , The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref>\n\nThe University of Winnipeg offers a Bachelor of Arts in Indigenous Studies with a master's degree in Indigenous Governance. The University of Winnipeg provides special first-year bridging programs for Aboriginal students. Academic counsellors, tutors, and Aboriginal Elders are present on campus to provide academic and social supports, as offered by The Aboriginal Student Services Center (ASSC) on campus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/assc/elders-in-residence.html|title=Elders in Residence {{!}} ASSC , The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref>\n\nThrough its Wii Chiiwaaknak Learning Centre, Eco-Kids Program and Eco-U Summer Camp services, the University of Winnipeg actively partners with Aboriginal communities. The University of Winnipeg is now offering the only master's degree in Development Practice with a focus on Indigenous Development in the world, joining a network of 22 prestigious universities globally with support from the MacArthur Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/index/cms-filesystem-action?file=pdfs/conferences/2007/aboriginal-rt-spring-report.pdf.|title=The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|accessdate=2 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080626101902/http://www.uwinnipeg.ca/index/cms-filesystem-action?file=pdfs%2Fconferences%2F2007%2Faboriginal-rt-spring-report.pdf|archive-date=26 June 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the university named broadcaster [[Wab Kinew]] as its first Director of Aboriginal Inclusion,<ref name=\"uwinnipeg\">[https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/index/uw-news-action/story.883/title.-uwinnipeg-names-first-director-of-indigenous-inclusion \"UWinnipeg names first Director of Indigenous Inclusion\"]. University of Winnipeg, 4 October 2012.</ref> a position designed to oversee the expansion of culturally inclusive outreach efforts and program development in First Nations education.<ref name=\"uwinnipeg\" />\n\n==The Collegiate==\nThe Collegiate at The University of Winnipeg is an on-site high school that offers Grades 9, 10, 11, and 12 programs.<ref name=FastFacts>[https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/about/fast-facts/index.html]</ref> It is an independent school and a division of The University of Winnipeg.<ref name=\"AboutCollegiate\" /> It offers an admission process intended to accelerate admission into first year university for Collegiate Students.<ref name=\"AboutCollegiate\" /> As of 2012, there are 353 students at The Collegiate.<ref name=\"FastFacts\" />\n\nThe Collegiate was created within Wesley College in 1873. At the time it was the only secondary school in Manitoba.<ref name=\"AboutCollegiate\">{{cite web|title=About the Collegiate|url=http://collegiate.uwinnipeg.ca/about.php|publisher=University of Winnipeg|accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n\n[[File:Duckworth_Centre.jpg|thumb|right|Duckworth Athletic Centre and Bill Wedlake Fitness Centre]]\n\n[[File:Axworthy Health & Recplex.jpg|thumb|right|Axworthy Health & RecPlex]]\n\nThe university is represented in [[U Sports]] by the [[Winnipeg Wesmen]] in volleyball, basketball, soccer, wrestling, as well as baseball. The U of W built a new field house (\" The RecPlex\"), named after Lloyd Axworthy, adjacent to the [[Duckworth Centre]] that provides indoor soccer services and smoothies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/campus-development/|title=Campus Development \u2013 The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-12}}</ref>\n\n==Library, Museum, Archives, and Art Gallery==\nThe [http://library.uwinnipeg.ca University of Winnipeg Library] supports the teaching and research needs of the university community through consultation services, research materials access, and spaces for study. In addition to administration of the Library, The Dean of the Library manages a portfolio that includes the copyright office, archives, art gallery, anthropology museum, and [http://winnspace.uwinnipeg.ca WinnSpace], the university's institutional repository.<ref>http://library.uwinnipeg.ca/about-us/staff-directory.html</ref> The library facility occupies the 4th and 5th floors of Centennial Hall, which was featured on the March 1973 cover of ''Progressive Architecture.''<ref>https://www.winnipegarchitecture.ca/centennial-hall-university-of-winnipeg/</ref>\n\nThe Anthropology Museum holds collections in ethnology, archaeology, primatology and hominid osteology which support the research, teaching, and public service functions of the Anthropology Department.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museevirtuel-virtualmuseum.ca/GetMuseumProfile.do?lang=en&chinCode=guantmu|title=Anthropology Museum at U of W|author=|date=|website=museevirtuel-virtualmuseum.ca|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe University of Winnipeg Archives<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.uwinnipeg.ca/|title=Home - Archives - The University of Winnipeg|website=archives.uwinnipeg.ca}}</ref> preserves and provides access to the records of the University of Winnipeg, as well as aspects of Manitoba history relevant to research at the University of Winnipeg, including social justice and human rights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.uwinnipeg.ca/about-us.html|title=About Us {{!}} Archives, The University of Winnipeg|last=|first=|date=|website=archives.uwinnipeg.ca|publisher=|accessdate=2017-01-25}}</ref>\n\n[[Gallery 1C03]] is the campus art gallery, located in Centennial Hall. The mission of the gallery is to, \"engage diverse communities through the development and presentation of contemporary and historical art exhibitions and related programming initiatives.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/art-gallery/|title=Home {{!}} Art Gallery, The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref> The gallery shows Manitoban, Canadian as well as international artists.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/art-gallery/about.html|title=About {{!}} Art Gallery, The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref> The gallery also works to develop, preserve and present the university's art collection.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/>\n\n==University administration==\n\n[[File:RiceCentreAdmin.jpg|thumb|right|The University of Winnipeg's administration offices and the student services centre are located at the Rice Centre.]]\nThe University of Winnipeg is a provincially and privately funded post-secondary institution with undergraduate and a growing number of graduate programs including Canada's only master's degree in development practice with a focus on Indigenous development, as well as a professional, applied and continuing education and a high school division.\n\nIt has had seven presidents since 1967 and Patrick Deane as an acting president for one school year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/index/admin-past-presidents|title=Past Presidents|work=President & Vice-Chancellor Lloyd Axworthy|publisher=University of Winnipeg|accessdate=23 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n# [[Wilfred Lockhart]] (1967\u20131971)\n# [[Henry Duckworth]] (1971\u20131981)\n# [[Robin Hugh Farquhar|Robin Farquhar]] (1981\u20131989)\n# [[Marsha Hanen]] (1989\u20131999)\n# Constance Rooke (1999\u20132003)\n# [[Patrick Deane (professor)|Patrick Deane]] (2003\u20132004; acting president)\n# [[Lloyd Axworthy]] (2004 \u2013 August 2014)\n# [[Annette Trimbee]] (August 2014 \u2013 present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/president/|title=President \u2013 The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-05}}</ref>\n\n==University history==\n* A. Gerald Bedford 'The University of Winnipeg: A History of the Founding Colleges' (Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1976)\n* Friesen, Gerald. \"Principal J. H. Riddell: The Sane and Safe Leader of Wesley College.\" In Prairie Spirit: Perspectives on the Heritage of the United Church of Canada in the West, edited by Dennis L. Butcher, et al. Winnipeg: University of Manitoba Press, 1985.\n\n===The Great Rock Climb===\n[[File:UWboulder.JPG|right|thumb|The granite boulder on the U of W's front lawn.]]\nThe University of Winnipeg has held their annual UWinnipeg Duckworth Great Rock Climb for over 67 years. The rock climb is traditionally held at the beginning of classes each year, on the front lawn of Portage Commons. The competition involves teams of three racing from Wesley Hall to the granite boulder monument on campus. The team to run and climb the rock the fastest wins. The fastest record was made at 9.4 seconds in 1979.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/50/news-and-events/events/2017/09/duckworth-great-rock-climb.html|title=Duckworth Great Rock Climb \u2013 50th Anniversary \u2013 The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-12}}</ref>\n\n==Noted alumni==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Ida Albo]] \u2013 businessperson\n* [[Lloyd Axworthy]] \u2013 politician and former UW President, Nobel prize nominee\n* [[Tom Axworthy]] \u2013 Canadian Civil Servant\n* [[Omar Zakhilwal]] \u2013 Afghan Finance Minister as well as the Chief Economic Advisor to the President of Afghanistan\n* [[David Bergen]] \u2013 Award-winning author (B.Ed. 1985)\n* [[Bill Blaikie]] \u2013 [[New Democratic Party|New Democratic]] [[Member of Parliament (Canada)|Member of Parliament]] and provincial cabinet minister\n* [[Margaret Bloodworth]] \u2013 National Security Advisor (BA 1970)\n* [[Alan Cross]] - radio personality\n* [[Ruby Dhalla]] \u2013 [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] Member of Parliament\n* [[Jaimie Isaac]] - artist and curator\n* [[Chantal Kreviazuk]] \u2013 singer/songwriter\n* [[Margaret Laurence]] \u2013 Canadian novelist and short-story writer\n* [[Guy Maddin]] \u2013 film director\n* [[Don Newman (broadcaster)|Don Newman]] \u2013 Award-winning journalist\n* [[John Paskievich]] \u2013 film director and photographer\n* [[Howard Pawley]] \u2013 former Premier of Manitoba\n* [[Fred Penner]] \u2013 children's entertainer\n* [[Susan Thompson]] \u2013 former mayor of Winnipeg\n* [[Brad Roberts]] \u2013 pop singer, [[Crash Test Dummies]]\n* [[Bill Richardson (radio)|Bill Richardson]] \u2013 [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] radio host\n* [[Erfan Nasajpour]] \u2013 professional basketball player\n* [[Andrea Slobodian]] \u2013 reporter<ref name=globalwinnipeg1>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalwinnipeg.com/Andrea+Slobodian/766679/story.html|title=Andrea Slobodian: Weather Anchor|date=11 March 2008|work=Global Winnipeg|publisher=Shaw Media Inc.|accessdate=12 December 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Sonia Sui]] \u2013 a model and actress in Taiwan\n* [[Lois Miriam Wilson|Lois Wilson]] \u2013 first female Moderator of the United Church of Canada\n* [[Vic Toews]] \u2013 Former Conservative MP and held different positions in Cabinet, Manitoba Judge\n* [[Dave Weasel]] - Comedian\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notable staff==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Jennifer S.H. Brown]], Tier 1 Canada Research Chair for Aboriginal Peoples in an Urban and Regional Context and Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Canada]]\n* [[Michael Weinrath]], founding chair (2004 to 2012) of Criminal Justice and Interdisciplinary Criminology, inaugural director (2013) of the Justice Research Institute\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n* [[List of universities in the Canadian Prairies]]\n* [[Higher education in Manitoba]]\n* [[U Sports]]\n* [[Canadian government scientific research organizations]]\n* [[Canadian university scientific research organizations]]\n* [[Canadian industrial research and development organizations]]\n* [[Education in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|University of Winnipeg}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.theuwsa.ca The University of Winnipeg Students' Association]\n* [http://dce.uwinnipegcourses.ca/ University of Winnipeg's Division of Continuing Education]\n* The Directory of Canadian Universities \u2013 [https://web.archive.org/web/20081218012814/http://www.aucc.ca/can_uni/our_universities/winnipeg_e.html University of Winnipeg]\n{{MB_Uni}}\n{{Can-sem}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:University Of Winnipeg}}\n[[Category:University of Winnipeg| ]]\n[[Category:Universities in Canada]]\n[[Category:Higher education in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=February 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2007}}\n{{Coord|49|53|24.44|N|97|9|12.12|W|display=title|type:edu}}\n{{Infobox university\n| image          = Uof Winnepeg CoA.svg\n| name           = University of Winnipeg\n| motto          = ''Lux et Veritas Floreant'' \n| mottoeng       = Let Light and Truth Flourish\n| established    = 1871 Manitoba College. Subsequent names, Wesley College (1881), United College (1938), and now, The University of Winnipeg (1967\u2013present)\n| type           = [[Public university|Public]]\n| president      = [[Annette Trimbee]]\n| city           = [[Winnipeg]]\n| province       = [[Manitoba]]\n| country        = Canada\n| students       = 9,419<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/about/fast-facts/index.html</ref>\n| undergrad      = 9,137<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/about/fast-facts/index.html</ref>\n| postgrad       = 282<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/about/fast-facts/index.html</ref>\n| academic_staff = 305<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/about/fast-facts/index.html</ref>\n| administrative_staff = 494<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/about/fast-facts/index.html</ref>\n| campus         = Urban\n| mascot         = Wesley Coyote\n| free_label     = Sports team\n| free           = [[Winnipeg Wesmen]]\n| affiliations   = [[Association of Universities and Colleges of Canada|AUCC]], [[International Association of Universities|IAU]], [[Association of Theological Schools in the United States and Canada|ATS]], [[U Sports]], [[Canada West Universities Athletic Association|CWUAA]], [[University of the Arctic|UArctic]], [[Campus Manitoba]], [[Canadian University Press|CUP]], [[Gallery 1C03]]\n| endowment      = [[Canadian dollar|$]]64.7 million<ref>{{cite web|title=The University of Winnipeg Foundation: 2017-2018 Annual Endowment report|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/foundation/docs/annual-report-2018-final.pdf|publisher=''The University of Winnipeg Foundation |accessdate= 28 June 2019}}</ref>\n| website        = {{URL|https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/}}\n| logo           = Uof Winnepeg Logo.svg\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Winnipeg''' ('''UWinnipeg''', '''U of W''') is a [[public research university]] in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], Canada, that offers undergraduate faculties of art, business and economics, education, science and kinesiology and applied health as well as graduate programs. UWinnipeg's founding colleges were [[Manitoba College]] and [[Wesley College, Winnipeg|Wesley College]], which merged to form [[United College, Winnipeg|United College]] in 1938. The University of Winnipeg was established in 1967 when United College received its charter. The governance was modeled on the provincial [[University of Toronto]] Act of 1906 which established a bicameral system of university government consisting of a senate (faculty), responsible for academic policy, and a board of governors (citizens) exercising exclusive control over financial policy and having formal authority in all other matters. The president, appointed by the board, was a link between the bodies to perform institutional leadership.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/ |title=The Canadian Encyclopedia |encyclopedia=The Canadian Encyclopedia |date=1936-02-07 |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref>\n\nThe University's current president and vice-chancellor, [[Annette Trimbee]], announced her resignation in March 2020. UWinnipeg's interim president will be James Currie, vice-president academic and provost until a new president is appointed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/university-winnipeg-president-resigns-1.5483785|title=University of Winnipeg president to leave job in July|last=|first=|date=March 3, 2020|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n[[Maclean's|''Maclean's'' magazine]] and ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' newspaper consistently rank the university in the top fifteen of all Canadian universities whose primary focus is undergraduate education in the category of student satisfaction. In 2013 the U of W ranked 13th out of 19 primarily undergraduate institutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oncampus.macleans.ca/education/2012/11/01/2013-primarily-undergraduate/. |title = 2013 Primarily undergraduate ranking |author = Maclean's |accessdate=8 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:UniversityofWinnipegFront.jpg|left|thumb|The University of Winnipeg]]\nThe U of W's founding colleges were [[Manitoba College]], 1871, and [[Wesley College, Winnipeg|Wesley College]], 1888, which merged to form United College in 1938.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/about/fast-facts/index.html|title=UWinnipeg Fast Facts|publisher=University of Winnipeg|accessdate=2016-10-20}}</ref><ref>Friesen, Gerald. \"Principal J. H. Riddell: The Sane and Safe Leader of Wesley College.\" In Prairie Spirit: Perspectives on the Heritage of the United Church of Canada in the West, edited by Dennis L. Butcher, et al. Winnipeg: University of Manitoba Press, 1985.</ref> In 1967, United College received a charter and became the University of Winnipeg. George Creeford Browne (architect) & S. Frank Peters designed Wesley Hall (1894\u20135), which is now part of the University of Winnipeg.<ref>[http://dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org/architects/view/1223 George Creeford Browne (architect) & S. Frank Peters]</ref>\n\nThe University of Winnipeg was established on 1 July 1967<ref>{{cite book|title=Fitzhenry and Whiteside Book of Canadian Facts and Dates|last=Pound|first=Richard W.|publisher=Fitzhenry and Whiteside|year=2005}}</ref> when United College received its charter.<ref name=\"Bedford, A. G 1976\">Bedford, A. G. The University of Winnipeg: A History of the Founding Colleges. Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1976.</ref>\nUnited College was formed in 1938 from the union of Manitoba College, founded in 1871, and Wesley College, founded in 1888. Originally affiliated with the [[University of Manitoba]], United College received its charter in 1967 and became the University of Winnipeg.<ref name=\"Bedford, A. G 1976\" />\n\n==Campus==\n[[File: Rice Centre.jpg|thumb|right|Rice Centre with the Buhler Centre seen in the back]]\n[[File:UofWRear.JPG|thumb|right|University of Winnipeg seen from Ellice Avenue]] \n[[File:UWBuhlerCentre.JPG|thumb|right|University of Winnipeg Buhler Centre]] \n[[File:UWTheatreandFilm.JPG|thumb|right|University of Winnipeg Theatre & Film]] \n\nThe campus of The University of Winnipeg is made up of 23 buildings spreading over several full blocks of [[Downtown Winnipeg]], located directly on [[Portage Avenue]].<ref>https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/map/docs/campus-map.pdf</ref> Over the past decade, the campus has undergone over 10 new building construction or major renovation projects. Through its revitalization, the University has become an engine for downtown renewal and improvement. <ref>http://uwcrc.ca/projects</ref>\n\n\nWesley Hall is a stone-clad brick structure built in 1894\u201395 and is on the Registry of Historic Places of Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=8224&pid=0|title=Wesley Hall|publisher=Canada's Historic Places|accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref> It is located on 515 Portage Ave. near [[Portage Place]] Mall.\n\nThe Buhler Centre was constructed to house the Faculty of Business and Economics, as well as PACE (Professional, Applied and Continuing Education), a division of the University of Winnipeg. The doors to the Buhler Centre opened September 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/index/campus-development-buhler-centre|title=Campus Development Buhler Centre|publisher=University of Winnipeg|accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref> Designed by PSA+DPA+DIN collective a collaborative effort between Peter Sampson Architecture Studio inc, David Penner Architect, and DIN Projects. The Buhler Centre also houses the Plug In Institute of Contemporary Art and Stella's Cafe on the main floor.\n\nThe Institute for stained glass in Canada has documented the stained glass at the University of Winnipeg. Specifically at the convocation hall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stainedglasscanada.ca/site.php?site=184/|title=Institute for stained glass in Canada|accessdate=16 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the university announced that Raymond L. McFeetors, Chairman of [[Great West Life|The Great West Life Assurance Company]], had donated $2.67 Million for a dormitory to be built on newly acquired property west of the campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/index/release-080502.|title=Ray McFeetors, Great West Life|author=University of Winnipeg|accessdate=13 July 2008}}</ref> The money came from his personal resources and from Great West Life.\n\n==Campus development==\n\n[[File: Marsha Hanen Way.jpg|thumb|right|Marsha Hanen Way with the Health & RecPlex in the back.]]\n[[File:Balmoral Transit Terminal at the University of Winnipeg.jpg|thumb|right| Balmoral University Transit Terminal]]\n\nCampus development, by the University of Winnipeg, is headed by The University of Winnipeg Renewal Corporation (UWCRC), \"a not-for-profit charitable corporation, spearheads and manages campus development.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/campus-development/|title=Campus Development \u2013 The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-11}}</ref> The UWCRC is a not-for-profit subsidiary of the University of Winnipeg and works to achieve environmental, social, economic and cultural sustainability. Their mandate is to \"apply [the UWCRC's] values, skills, competencies, and experience to non-University specific economic development activities. [UWCRC] is mandated to develop wholly owned or joint-venture real estate developments and to provide development, project management and property management services to other post-secondary institutions, non-profit organizations and First Nations clients.\"<ref name=\"uwinnipeg.ca\">{{Cite web|url=http://uwcrc.ca/what-we-do|title=What We Do {{!}} The University of Winnipeg Community Renewal Corporation|website=uwcrc.ca|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-11}}</ref>\n\nThe university president sits as the chair of the corporation and participates in its business partnerships.\n\nThe structure of the UWCRC is unique in Canada as it allows the corporation to avoid being governed by the strictures of university governance.<ref name=\"uwinnipeg.ca\" /> The corporation serves as \"a primary engine for the redevelopment of Winnipeg\u2019s downtown\", a task traditionally undertaken by government and the private sector, and not educational institutions.<ref name=\"uwinnipeg.ca\" />\n\nRecent initiatives include the newly renovated Asper Centre for Theater and Film, Richardson College for the Environment and Science Complex, The Axworthy Health and RecPlex, McFeetors Hall (a new student residence) and the UWSA Daycare.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/campus-development/|title=Campus Development \u2013 The University of Winnipeg|last=|first=|date=|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-11}}</ref> A new mixed use 14-story apartment complex for students and the community began construction in 2015.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nThe financial statements of the corporation are not publicly available under public disclosure legislation. The corporate draws its operating funds entirely from the university budget.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/financial-services/financial-statements.html|title=Audited Financial Statements and Other Financial Information - Financial Services, The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca}}</ref>\n\n==Academic==\n===Students and faculty===\nStudents at the university are represented by the University of Winnipeg Students' Association.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theuwsa.ca|title=The University of Winnipeg's Student Association|accessdate=16 February 2010}}</ref> [[CKUW]] is the [[student radio]] station based at the University of Winnipeg. The Uniter is the campus newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uniter.ca/|title=The Uniter|accessdate=16 February 2010}}</ref> The Student Services staff are represented by AESES.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aeses.ca/|title=Home - Association of Employees Supporting Education Services|website=Association of Employees Supporting Education Services}}</ref>\n\n===Faculties===\n* Faculty of Arts\n* Faculty of Education\n* Gupta Faculty of Kinesiology and Applied Health \n* Faculty of Science\n* Faculty of Graduate Studies\n* [[University of Winnipeg's Faculty of Business and Economics]]\n\n===Colleges===\n* Global College\n* Menno Simons College\n* Richardson College for the Environment\n\n===Centres and institutes===\n* Centre for Academic Writing (CAW)\n* Centre for Distributed / Distance Learning (CDDL)\n* Centre for Forest Interdisciplinary Research (C-FIR)\n* Centre for Innovation in Teaching & Learning (CITL)\n* Centre for Learning and Secular Society (CLASS)\n* Centre for Research in Young People's Texts and Cultures (CRYTC)\n* Centre for Rupert's Land Studies\n* Centre for Sustainable Transportation\n* Centre for Terrestrial and Planetary Exploration (C-TAPE)\n* Institute of Urban Studies\n* Institute for Women's and Gender Studies\n* India Centre for Academic, Business, and Community Excellence\n\n=== Graduate programs ===\n* Masters of Arts in Cultural Studies\n* Master of Arts in Indigenous Governance\n* Master of Arts in Environmental, Resource, and Developmental Economics (ERDE)\n* Master of Arts in Criminal Justice (as of Fall 2018)\n* Master of Science in Applied Computer Science and Society\n* Master of Science in Bioscience, Technology and Public Policy\n* Master's in Development Practice: Indigenous Development\n* Master's in Management: Technology, Innovation and Operations.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/graduate-studies/graduate-programs/|title=Programs Overview {{!}} Graduate Studies , The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref>\nMaster in Sacred Theology and Master of Arts Spiritual Disciplines & Ministry Practices are under review. Applications are not currently being accepted by the University of Winnipeg.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n==== Joint programs with the University of Manitoba ====\n* Master of Arts in History\n* Master of Public Administration\n* Master of Arts in Religious Studies\n* Master of Arts in Peace and Conflict Studies<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n==== Postgraduate certificates ====\n* The Higher Education Teaching Certificate\n* The Postgraduate Professional Skills Certificate<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n==Indigenous UWinnipeg ==\nThe University of Winnipeg offers several programs and services to Aboriginal people. It is the first university to mandate that all students take an Indigenous course requirement as part of their degree. The course was added by the University of Winnipeg in support and compliance with the recommendations by the [[Truth and Reconciliation Commission of Canada]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/indigenous-course-requirement/index.html|title=Home {{!}} Indigenous Course Requirement , The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref>\n\nThe University of Winnipeg offers a Bachelor of Arts in Indigenous Studies with a master's degree in Indigenous Governance. The University of Winnipeg provides special first-year bridging programs for Aboriginal students. Academic counsellors, tutors, and Aboriginal Elders are present on campus to provide academic and social supports, as offered by The Aboriginal Student Services Center (ASSC) on campus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/assc/elders-in-residence.html|title=Elders in Residence {{!}} ASSC , The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref>\n\nThrough its Wii Chiiwaaknak Learning Centre, Eco-Kids Program and Eco-U Summer Camp services, the University of Winnipeg actively partners with Aboriginal communities. The University of Winnipeg is now offering the only master's degree in Development Practice with a focus on Indigenous Development in the world, joining a network of 22 prestigious universities globally with support from the MacArthur Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/index/cms-filesystem-action?file=pdfs/conferences/2007/aboriginal-rt-spring-report.pdf.|title=The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|accessdate=2 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080626101902/http://www.uwinnipeg.ca/index/cms-filesystem-action?file=pdfs%2Fconferences%2F2007%2Faboriginal-rt-spring-report.pdf|archive-date=26 June 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the university named broadcaster [[Wab Kinew]] as its first Director of Aboriginal Inclusion,<ref name=\"uwinnipeg\">[https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/index/uw-news-action/story.883/title.-uwinnipeg-names-first-director-of-indigenous-inclusion \"UWinnipeg names first Director of Indigenous Inclusion\"]. University of Winnipeg, 4 October 2012.</ref> a position designed to oversee the expansion of culturally inclusive outreach efforts and program development in First Nations education.<ref name=\"uwinnipeg\" />\n\n==The Collegiate==\nThe Collegiate at The University of Winnipeg is an on-site high school that offers Grades 9, 10, 11, and 12 programs.<ref name=FastFacts>[https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/about/fast-facts/index.html]</ref> It is an independent school and a division of The University of Winnipeg.<ref name=\"AboutCollegiate\" /> It offers an admission process intended to accelerate admission into first year university for Collegiate Students.<ref name=\"AboutCollegiate\" /> As of 2012, there are 353 students at The Collegiate.<ref name=\"FastFacts\" />\n\nThe Collegiate was created within Wesley College in 1873. At the time it was the only secondary school in Manitoba.<ref name=\"AboutCollegiate\">{{cite web|title=About the Collegiate|url=http://collegiate.uwinnipeg.ca/about.php|publisher=University of Winnipeg|accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n\n[[File:Duckworth_Centre.jpg|thumb|right|Duckworth Athletic Centre and Bill Wedlake Fitness Centre]] \n\n[[File:Axworthy Health & Recplex.jpg|thumb|right|Axworthy Health & RecPlex]] \n\nThe university is represented in [[U Sports]] by the [[Winnipeg Wesmen]] in volleyball, basketball, soccer, wrestling, as well as baseball. The U of W built a new field house (\" The RecPlex\"), named after Lloyd Axworthy, adjacent to the [[Duckworth Centre]] that provides indoor soccer services and smoothies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/campus-development/|title=Campus Development \u2013 The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-12}}</ref>\n\n==Library, Museum, Archives, and Art Gallery==\nThe [http://library.uwinnipeg.ca University of Winnipeg Library] supports the teaching and research needs of the university community through consultation services, research materials access, and spaces for study. In addition to administration of the Library, The Dean of the Library manages a portfolio that includes the copyright office, archives, art gallery, anthropology museum, and [http://winnspace.uwinnipeg.ca WinnSpace], the university's institutional repository.<ref>http://library.uwinnipeg.ca/about-us/staff-directory.html</ref> The library facility occupies the 4th and 5th floors of Centennial Hall, which was featured on the March 1973 cover of ''Progressive Architecture.''<ref>https://www.winnipegarchitecture.ca/centennial-hall-university-of-winnipeg/</ref>\n\nThe Anthropology Museum holds collections in ethnology, archaeology, primatology and hominid osteology which support the research, teaching, and public service functions of the Anthropology Department.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museevirtuel-virtualmuseum.ca/GetMuseumProfile.do?lang=en&chinCode=guantmu|title=Anthropology Museum at U of W|author=|date=|website=museevirtuel-virtualmuseum.ca|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe University of Winnipeg Archives<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.uwinnipeg.ca/|title=Home - Archives - The University of Winnipeg|website=archives.uwinnipeg.ca}}</ref> preserves and provides access to the records of the University of Winnipeg, as well as aspects of Manitoba history relevant to research at the University of Winnipeg, including social justice and human rights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.uwinnipeg.ca/about-us.html|title=About Us {{!}} Archives, The University of Winnipeg|last=|first=|date=|website=archives.uwinnipeg.ca|publisher=|accessdate=2017-01-25}}</ref>\n\n[[Gallery 1C03]] is the campus art gallery, located in Centennial Hall. The mission of the gallery is to, \"engage diverse communities through the development and presentation of contemporary and historical art exhibitions and related programming initiatives.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/art-gallery/|title=Home {{!}} Art Gallery, The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref> The gallery shows Manitoban, Canadian as well as international artists.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/art-gallery/about.html|title=About {{!}} Art Gallery, The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref> The gallery also works to develop, preserve and present the university's art collection.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/>\n\n==University administration==\n\n[[File:RiceCentreAdmin.jpg|thumb|right|The University of Winnipeg's administration offices and the student services centre are located at the Rice Centre.]]\nThe University of Winnipeg is a provincially and privately funded post-secondary institution with undergraduate and a growing number of graduate programs including Canada's only master's degree in development practice with a focus on Indigenous development, as well as a professional, applied and continuing education and a high school division.\n\nIt has had seven presidents since 1967 and Patrick Deane as an acting president for one school year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/index/admin-past-presidents|title=Past Presidents|work=President & Vice-Chancellor Lloyd Axworthy|publisher=University of Winnipeg|accessdate=23 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n# [[Wilfred Lockhart]] (1967\u20131971)\n# [[Henry Duckworth]] (1971\u20131981)\n# [[Robin Hugh Farquhar|Robin Farquhar]] (1981\u20131989)\n# [[Marsha Hanen]] (1989\u20131999)\n# Constance Rooke (1999\u20132003)\n# [[Patrick Deane (professor)|Patrick Deane]] (2003\u20132004; acting president)\n# [[Lloyd Axworthy]] (2004 \u2013 August 2014)\n# [[Annette Trimbee]] (August 2014 \u2013 present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/president/|title=President \u2013 The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-05}}</ref>\n\n==University history==\n* A. Gerald Bedford 'The University of Winnipeg: A History of the Founding Colleges' (Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1976)\n* Friesen, Gerald. \"Principal J. H. Riddell: The Sane and Safe Leader of Wesley College.\" In Prairie Spirit: Perspectives on the Heritage of the United Church of Canada in the West, edited by Dennis L. Butcher, et al. Winnipeg: University of Manitoba Press, 1985.\n\n===The Great Rock Climb===\n[[File:UWboulder.JPG|right|thumb|The granite boulder on the U of W's front lawn.]]\nThe University of Winnipeg has held their annual UWinnipeg Duckworth Great Rock Climb for over 67 years. The rock climb is traditionally held at the beginning of classes each year, on the front lawn of Portage Commons. The competition involves teams of three racing from Wesley Hall to the granite boulder monument on campus. The team to run and climb the rock the fastest wins. The fastest record was made at 9.4 seconds in 1979.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwinnipeg.ca/50/news-and-events/events/2017/09/duckworth-great-rock-climb.html|title=Duckworth Great Rock Climb \u2013 50th Anniversary \u2013 The University of Winnipeg|website=www.uwinnipeg.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-10-12}}</ref>\n\n==Noted alumni==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Ida Albo]] \u2013 businessperson\n* [[Lloyd Axworthy]] \u2013 politician and former UW President, Nobel prize nominee\n* [[Tom Axworthy]] \u2013 Canadian Civil Servant\n* [[Omar Zakhilwal]] \u2013 Afghan Finance Minister as well as the Chief Economic Advisor to the President of Afghanistan\n* [[David Bergen]] \u2013 Award-winning author (B.Ed. 1985)\n* [[Bill Blaikie]] \u2013 [[New Democratic Party|New Democratic]] [[Member of Parliament (Canada)|Member of Parliament]] and provincial cabinet minister\n* [[Margaret Bloodworth]] \u2013 National Security Advisor (BA 1970)\n* [[Alan Cross]] - radio personality\n* [[Ruby Dhalla]] \u2013 [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] Member of Parliament\n* [[Jaimie Isaac]] - artist and curator\n* [[Chantal Kreviazuk]] \u2013 singer/songwriter\n* [[Margaret Laurence]] \u2013 Canadian novelist and short-story writer\n* [[Guy Maddin]] \u2013 film director\n* [[Don Newman (broadcaster)|Don Newman]] \u2013 Award-winning journalist\n* [[John Paskievich]] \u2013 film director and photographer\n* [[Howard Pawley]] \u2013 former Premier of Manitoba\n* [[Fred Penner]] \u2013 children's entertainer\n* [[Susan Thompson]] \u2013 former mayor of Winnipeg\n* [[Brad Roberts]] \u2013 pop singer, [[Crash Test Dummies]]\n* [[Bill Richardson (radio)|Bill Richardson]] \u2013 [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] radio host\n* [[Erfan Nasajpour]] \u2013 professional basketball player\n* [[Andrea Slobodian]] \u2013 reporter<ref name=globalwinnipeg1>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalwinnipeg.com/Andrea+Slobodian/766679/story.html|title=Andrea Slobodian: Weather Anchor|date=11 March 2008|work=Global Winnipeg|publisher=Shaw Media Inc.|accessdate=12 December 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Sonia Sui]] \u2013 a model and actress in Taiwan\n* [[Lois Miriam Wilson|Lois Wilson]] \u2013 first female Moderator of the United Church of Canada\n* [[Vic Toews]] \u2013 Former Conservative MP and held different positions in Cabinet, Manitoba Judge\n* [[Dave Weasel]] - Comedian\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notable staff==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Jennifer S.H. Brown]], Tier 1 Canada Research Chair for Aboriginal Peoples in an Urban and Regional Context and Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Canada]]\n* [[Michael Weinrath]], founding chair (2004 to 2012) of Criminal Justice and Interdisciplinary Criminology, inaugural director (2013) of the Justice Research Institute\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n* [[List of universities in the Canadian Prairies]]\n* [[Higher education in Manitoba]]\n* [[U Sports]]\n* [[Canadian government scientific research organizations]]\n* [[Canadian university scientific research organizations]]\n* [[Canadian industrial research and development organizations]]\n* [[Education in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|University of Winnipeg}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.theuwsa.ca The University of Winnipeg Students' Association]\n* [http://dce.uwinnipegcourses.ca/ University of Winnipeg's Division of Continuing Education]\n* The Directory of Canadian Universities \u2013 [https://web.archive.org/web/20081218012814/http://www.aucc.ca/can_uni/our_universities/winnipeg_e.html University of Winnipeg]\n{{MB_Uni}}\n{{Can-sem}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:University Of Winnipeg}}\n[[Category:University of Winnipeg| ]]\n[[Category:Universities in Canada]]\n[[Category:Higher education in Canada]]\n", "name_us