{"title_page": "Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation COVID model", "text_new": "{{short description|Infectious disease model}}\n\nThe '''Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation COVID model''' (IHME model), also called the \"[[Christopher J. L. Murray|Chris Murray]] model\" after the IHME director, is an [[Mathematical modelling of infectious disease|epidemiological model]] for [[COVID-19]] developed at the [[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]] at the [[University of Washington]] in [[Seattle]]. The model has been termed \"perhaps the most widely cited coronavirus model\" by ''[[The Colorado Sun]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Three coronavirus models have very different takes on how Colorado's outbreak will develop|author=John Ingold|date=April 7, 2020|newspaper=[[The Colorado Sun]]|url=https://coloradosun.com/2020/04/07/colorado-coronavirus-cases-models/}}</ref> \"America's most influential coronavirus model\" by ''[[The Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=America's most influential coronavirus model just revised its estimates downward. But not every model agrees.|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|authors= \nWilliam Wan and Carolyn Y. Johnson|date=April 8, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/04/08/leading-model-now-estimates-tens-thousands-fewer-covid-19-deaths-by-summer/}}</ref> and its projections were cited during White House briefings in March\u2013April 2020.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[NPR]]|title=Coronavirus State-By-State Projections: When Will Each State Peak?|date=April 7, 2020|author=Sean McMinn|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/04/07/825479416/new-yorks-coronavirus-deaths-may-level-off-soon-when-might-your-state-s-peak}}</ref>\n\nCritics say the model uses flawed methods and shouldn\u2019t guide U.S. policies.<ref>{{cite news|title=Influential COVID-19 model uses flawed methods and shouldn\u2019t guide U.S. policies, critics say |publisher=[[Stat News]]|date=April 17, 2020|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/04/17/influential-covid-19-model-uses-flawed-methods-shouldnt-guide-policies-critics-say}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citation|journal=[[Annals of Internal Medicine]]|title=Caution Warranted: Using the Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation Model for Predicting the Course of the COVID-19 Pandemic|author1-first=Nicholas P. |author1-last=Jewell|author2-first=Joseph A. |author2-last=Lewnard|author3-first=Britta L. |author3-last=Jewell|date=April 14, 2020|url=https://annals.org/aim/fullarticle/2764774/caution-warranted-using-institute-health-metrics-evaluation-model-predicting-course}}\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.healthdata.org/covid\n\n[[Category:COVID-19]]\n[[Category:Epidemiology]]\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Infectious disease model}}\n\nThe '''Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation COVID model''' (IHME model), also called the \"[[Christopher J. L. Murray|Chris Murray]] model\" after the IHME director, is an [[Mathematical modelling of infectious disease|epidemiological model]] for [[COVID-19]] developed at the [[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]] at the [[University of Washington]] in [[Seattle]]. The model has been termed \"perhaps the most widely cited coronavirus model\" by ''[[The Colorado Sun]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Three coronavirus models have very different takes on how Colorado's outbreak will develop|author=John Ingold|date=April 7, 2020|newspaper=[[The Colorado Sun]]|url=https://coloradosun.com/2020/04/07/colorado-coronavirus-cases-models/}}</ref> \"America's most influential coronavirus model\" by ''[[The Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=America's most influential coronavirus model just revised its estimates downward. But not every model agrees.|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|authors= \nWilliam Wan and Carolyn Y. Johnson|date=April 8, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/04/08/leading-model-now-estimates-tens-thousands-fewer-covid-19-deaths-by-summer/}}</ref> and its projections were cited during White House briefings in March\u2013April 2020.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[NPR]]|title=Coronavirus State-By-State Projections: When Will Each State Peak?|date=April 7, 2020|author=Sean McMinn|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/04/07/825479416/new-yorks-coronavirus-deaths-may-level-off-soon-when-might-your-state-s-peak}}</ref>\n\nCritics say the model uses flawed methods and shouldn\u2019t guide U.S. policies.<ref>https://www.statnews.com/2020/04/17/influential-covid-19-model-uses-flawed-methods-shouldnt-guide-policies-critics-say</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citation|journal=[[Annals of Internal Medicine]]|title=Caution Warranted: Using the Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation Model for Predicting the Course of the COVID-19 Pandemic|author1-first=Nicholas P. |author1-last=Jewell|author2-first=Joseph A. |author2-last=Lewnard|author3-first=Britta L. |author3-last=Jewell|date=April 14, 2020|url=https://annals.org/aim/fullarticle/2764774/caution-warranted-using-institute-health-metrics-evaluation-model-predicting-course}}\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.healthdata.org/covid\n\n[[Category:COVID-19]]\n[[Category:Epidemiology]]\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bri", "label": "safe", "comment": "fmt ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Institute_for_Health_Metrics_and_Evaluation_COVID_model"}
